Local engagement as an antidote to populism.
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies were shaken to their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble one another everywhere in the West.
The leadership of the once dominant parties oscillates between denial and desperation, while populists are fishing out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters as "pitiful" to their opponents, much like Hillary Clinton did, shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too intimidated by the populist tide to launch a counterattack.
Neither denial nor complacency will dissolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reorganize, and this begins with a diagnosis of the shortcomings of the traditional parties.
A significant part of the problem lies in the fact that the traditional parties have failed to recognize the true issues of our time.
Still confined to the old ideological battlegrounds, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the growing geographical inequality, the tensions surrounding multiculturalism, and other issues that truly matter to voters.
In decades past, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are all alone in the woods, wondering where everyone has gone.
Social sciences could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened to a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have been aware for a long time of the growing gap in income and other indicators between some affluent, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
But it wasn't until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, that no national head of government had implemented tax cuts based on residence.
In consequence of this policy, 1% of the French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Many traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters rather than solely through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest doorstep survey in French history.
What the voters told the questioners then became the basis for Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected numerous statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual harassment of women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
Macron's stance at the time made him the target of jokes from his opponents; however, their laughter soon faded with the emergence of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
Many traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
That was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace, consisting of state suppliers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, a party's sole purpose in existence is to seize and maintain power.
It's no wonder that citizens and even party members themselves feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to the elections, organize protests, and start petitions.
This model no longer works.
The citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy today.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation emerged.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own rights and not as pawns in the game of others.
In addition, governments themselves are no longer the sole suppliers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn in the two years that we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most pressing political challenges of today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – cannot be addressed by national governments alone.
These challenges demand profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on their established dominance and entrenched support networks.
Those who can effectively navigate Google, Twitter, and Facebook do not need a centuries-old party apparatus.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures rather than just elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an "administrative back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
We refer to this as local citizen projects at La République En Marche!.
These can range from literacy courses after school and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering tailored solutions for local problems and thereby strengthening the community.
We should consider such projects as indispensable complements to state policy today.
In the future, a party's ability to offer attractive pathways for political and community engagement will be crucial to its appeal.
And by daily "live" demonstrating their reform policy, the parties will then have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Reestablishing the connection to the voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting the party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics on the ground.
